---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";

const birthDate = new Date("2003-03-18T00:00:00");
const now = new Date();

const diff = now.getTime() - birthDate.getTime();
const age = diff / (1000 * 60 * 60 * 24 * 365.2425);

// clean numeric value (1 decimal)
const liveAge = Math.round(age * 10) / 10;
---

<Layout title="Origin Story">
  <h1>Origin Story</h1>

  <p>
    I was born on <strong>18/03/2003</strong> (currently <strong>{liveAge} years old</strong>),
    in a remote village where life was simple and slow. Technology was not something I grew up around but curiosity showed up early anyway.
  </p>

  <p>
    My first real exposure to tech was not code or systems, it was Hollywood movies, especially Marvel. Iron Man, Transformers, Alien, and Nolan movies.
    That world felt bigger than life and that is probably where imagination started shaping things.
  </p>

  <p>
    Around 7th standard, I got my first computer. I did not really understand it at first.
    I just played GTA San Andreas, Need for Speed, IGI… hours disappeared into games.
    But slowly, I started enjoying exploring the machine more than just playing.
  </p>

  <p>
    After school, things became uncertain. I started preparing for government jobs thinking stability was the goal.
    I finished 12th, kept preparing, kept attempting exams, and then COVID happened.
  </p>

  <p>
    That period changed things. My curiosity about computers came back stronger.
    I could not take admission in engineering back then, so I joined BSc at my local college while continuing both government job preparation and tech as a backup. Some things did not work out and other personal aspects of my life also played a role which I cannot talk about here.
  </p>

  <p>
    For a while, tech was just a backup plan. Government jobs felt safe but limiting.
    I slowly realized I did not just want stability. I wanted growth, money, and control over what I build.
  </p>

  <p>
    By the end of graduation, I got an offer from TCS through mass recruitment.
    At the same time, I was deep into Discord communities, open source spaces, and meeting people online.
    That is where I met some like minded people, Rajat is one of them.
    <br />
    👉 <a href="https://pixel.meetrajat.com/" target="_blank">Check out Rajat’s space</a>
  </p>

  <p>
    Around the same time, I discovered
    <a href="https://buildspace.so/" target="_blank">buildspace</a>, a place where people just build and ship things. That mindset stuck.

    I wanted to build something unique, so I did not build much at first. I just observed and watched people building products, scaling startups, going to the US, chasing YC, and dreaming big. I also thought I would build something someday, go to the US, and raise money.

    But it is a long game. My goal at that moment became getting my first job. I did not have much proof of work, and people require that when you want to get a job. So I started cold outreach and somehow landed my first internship at a small service based startup. By that time, they did not even have a proper office.

    It was my first time in Pune. The nerd in me finally got into a big city on my own. It was tough, I was 21, everything was new, and I was earning 12K a month during my internship. But it felt like a lot because I was barely surviving on my own in the city.

    At the internship, there were people who had done CDAC, BTech, MCA, all from good colleges. I was the only person without much experience and with a BSc CS degree. Yet I got converted to full time the fastest, I earned it.

    I was disciplined. I worked hard. I delivered more than what was asked of me. People with me left, but I stayed. I pushed through. Alongside, I also took time for myself, stepped away from the grind a bit, enjoyed Pune, traveled, made memories, and met new friends.

    But this is just the beginning of a great journey. There is more to it, more to win in life.
  </p>

  <p>
    Getting my first job was not easy. There were setbacks, gaps, and uncertainty after graduation.
    But eventually it worked out and that gave me clarity.
  </p>

  <p>
    I went all in. I worked hard, delivered results, and slowly built confidence.
  </p>

